    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-10-21T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-10-21T19:00:00-05:00" n="202"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d202">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">762.022/10–2254: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_DILLONCD1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dillon</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d202fn1">Repeated to London and Bonn.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-10-22T01:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 22, 1954—1 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1691. At <persName corresp="#p_MENDESFP1">Mendes</persName>’s request, <persName
                        corresp="#p_PARODIA1">Parodi</persName> has just given British Embassy and
                    ourselves following account of state of Saar negotiations: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Despite apparently conciliatory German attitude on Tuesday, <persName
                                corresp="#p_ADENAUERK1">Adenauer</persName>’s position following his
                            talk with political leaders yesterday morning hardened all along the
                            line, principally on three points. The first was that he was no longer
                            prepared to speak of Saar “statute” but only of “reglement”, a much
                            weaker word denoting temporary arrangement subject to change at any
                            time. Second, was German insistence on Landtag elections as substitute
                            for referendum. Third, was German rejection of French proposals for
                            increased German-Saar trade and insistence on measures to expedite
                            German participation in management of mines, banks, and insurance
                            companies with view to developing German-Saar relationship approximating
                            present French-Saar relationship. He concluded that <persName
                                corresp="#p_ADENAUERK1">Adenauer</persName> this morning indicated
                            reluctance even to discuss the Saar further.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0394" n="1462" xml:id="pg_1462"/>
                <p>We are seeking German version.<note n="2" xml:id="d202fn2">In telegram 1696 from
                        Paris, Oct. 22, <persName corresp="#p_DILLONCD1">Dillon</persName> informed
                        the Department of State that <persName corresp="#p_BLANKENHORNHAH1"
                            >Blankenhorn</persName> generally confirmed the account given by
                            <persName corresp="#p_PARODIA1">Parodi</persName>. <persName
                            corresp="#p_DILLONCD1">Dillon</persName> noted that while <persName
                            corresp="#p_ADENAUERK1">Adenauer</persName> did not attach too much
                        importance to the Saar Agreement being reached immediately, <persName
                            corresp="#p_MENDESFP1">Mendès-France</persName> told the French press
                        that he would sign nothing unless the Saar accord was reached.
                        (762.022/10–2254)</note> French Cabinet is meeting at noon on Saar.
                        <persName corresp="#p_EDENSA1">Eden</persName> is lunching with <persName
                        corresp="#p_MENDESFP1">Mendes</persName> and is having <persName
                        corresp="#p_MENDESFP1">Mendes</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_ADENAUERK1">Adenauer</persName> for dinner this evening.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DILLONCD1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dillon</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
